euwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Melsbach, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Duitsland","Evangelisch, Rengsdorf, Rheinland, Prussia":"Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rijnland, Preußen","Germany":"Duitsland"},"en":{"1619–":"1619–Deceased","1630–1722":"1630–1722","1650–1715":"1650–1715","1619–Male":"1619–Deceased","1722":"1722","1630":"1630","Abt 1650":"1650","26 Jun 1704":"26 June 1704","1650":"1650","1619":"1619","1715":"1715","Rengsdorf, , Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Melsbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Melsbach, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Evangelisch, Rengsdorf, Rheinland, Prussia":"Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rhineland, Prussia","Germany":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from Middle High German and Middle Low German <i>kelle</i> ‘trowel’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker or user of such tools.","German: habitational name from any of the places, especially in Rhineland, named Kell, from Middle Low German <i>kel</i> (a field name denoting swampy land), or from <i>kelle</i> ‘steep path, ravine’ (see   Kelle  ).","English (northern): from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kel</i>, <i>Kæl</i>, shortened from <i>Áskell</i> (from <i>Ásketill</i>), <i>Ulkel</i> (from <i>Ulfkil</i>), or similar, rather than from the single-element name <i>Ketill</i> (see   Kettle  ) or its descendants, the shortening of which in Scandinavia occurs later."],"variants":[{"name":"Kellman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Ari, Chaya, Meyer, Yaakov.","Americanized form of German <b>Kellmann</b>: elaborated variant of   Kell   2, with the addition of <i>-mann</i> ‘man’. Compare   Kelman  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Kalman  ."]},{"name":"Kells","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: from a personal name based on Old Norse <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’, with post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>. In Scotland, it may also be of topographic origin, from a place called as ‘the cauldron’.","English: variant of   Kell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Kelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Klaus.","German: topographic name from the dialect word <i>Kelle</i> ‘steep path, ravine’."]},{"name":"Kellenberger","meanings":["German: habitational name for someone from a place called Kellenberg in Rhineland (see   Kell   2) or Lower Saxony."]},{"name":"Kellen","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place so named in Rhineland (see   Kell   2)."]}]},{"name":"Georg","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Wilhelm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>wil</i> ‘will’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet’; an ancient royal name.  See also  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Georg Wilhelm Kell was born in 1619, in Melsbach, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany. He married Gertraut Winn on 26 June 1704, in Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rhineland, Prussia. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Germany."},"et":{"1619–":"1619–Surnud","1630–1722":"1630–1722","1650–1715":"1650–1715","1619–Male":"1619–Surnud","1722":"1722","1630":"1630","Abt 1650":"1650","26 Jun 1704":"26. juuni 1704","1650":"1650","1619":"1619","1715":"1715","Rengsdorf, , Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Rengsdorf, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Melsbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Melsbach, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Evangelisch, Rengsdorf, Rheinland, Prussia":"Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Germany":"Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1619–":"1619–Kuollut","1630–1722":"1630–1722","1650–1715":"1650–1715","1619–Male":"1619–Kuollut","1722":"1722","1630":"1630","Abt 1650":"1650","26 Jun 1704":"26. kesäkuuta 1704","1650":"1650","1619":"1619","1715":"1715","Rengsdorf, , Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Rengsdorf, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksa","Melsbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Me